  "prompt": "Is 291 a good score in gre?",
  "response": "The **Graduate Record Examination (GRE)** is a standardized test commonly required for admission to many graduate programs. Understanding your GRE score in context is essential for evaluating how competitive you are for your desired programs.\n\n### **GRE Scoring Overview**\n\nThe GRE General Test consists of three main sections:\n\n1. **Verbal Reasoning**: Scores range from **130 to 170** (in 1-point increments).\n2. **Quantitative Reasoning**: Scores range from **130 to 170** (in 1-point increments).\n3. **Analytical Writing**: Scores range from **0 to 6** (in half-point increments).\n\nThe **total composite score** combines the Verbal and Quantitative sections, ranging from **260 to 340**.\n\n### **Interpreting a Total Score of 291**\n\nA **total GRE score of 291** typically breaks down into something like:\n- **Verbal Reasoning**: ~140\n- **Quantitative Reasoning**: ~151\n\n**Here's how a 291 score stands:**\n\n1. **Percentile Ranking**:\n   - A 291 total score generally falls **below the 50th percentile**, meaning you scored higher than approximately **40-45%** of test-takers.\n\n2. **Comparison to Averages**:\n   - **Average GRE Scores** (based on recent ETS data):\n     - **Verbal Reasoning**: ~150\n     - **Quantitative Reasoning**: ~152\n     - **Total**: ~302\n\n   - **291** is **below the average total score**.\n\n3. **Program Competitiveness**:\n   - **Highly Competitive Programs** (e.g., top-tier STEM fields, prestigious universities):\n     - Often expect GRE scores **well above the average**.\n     - A 291 might be **below** the typical range for these programs.\n\n   - **Moderately Competitive Programs**:\n     - May have average GRE scores closer to **295-310**.\n     - A 291 could be **on the lower side** but might still be **competitive** depending on other application factors.\n\n   - **Less Competitive Programs**:\n     - Some programs, particularly in certain humanities or social sciences, may be **more flexible** with GRE scores.\n\n### **Other Considerations**\n\n1. **Section Strengths**:\n   - If your **Quantitative** score is stronger relative to your **Verbal** score (or vice versa), it might align better with specific program requirements. For example, engineering programs often prioritize Quantitative scores.\n\n2. **Holistic Admissions**:\n   - Many graduate programs consider multiple factors beyond GRE scores, including:\n     - **Undergraduate GPA**\n     - **Letters of Recommendation**\n     - **Statement of Purpose**\n     - **Relevant Experience**\n\n3. **Improving Your Profile**:\n   - If your GRE score is below your target program's average, consider:\n     - **Retaking the GRE** to improve your score.\n     - **Highlighting strengths** in other areas of your application.\n     - **Addressing any weaknesses** through relevant experience or coursework.\n\n### **Conclusion**\n\nA **GRE score of 291** is **below the average** for many graduate programs, particularly those that are highly competitive. However, its competitiveness can vary based on the specific program and how it weighs different aspects of your application. It's essential to:\n\n- **Research the average GRE scores** for the programs you're interested in.\n- **Assess your entire application profile** to identify strengths and areas for improvement.\n- **Consider retaking the GRE** if you believe you can achieve a higher score that aligns better with your target programs.\n\nIf you have specific programs in mind, reaching out to their admissions offices for insights on average GRE scores can provide more tailored guidance.",
